=> Module Import Declarations (JEP 511)

    -> Earlier in Java, if we wanted to use classes from different packages,
       we had to import each package or class separately.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example Before Module Import Declarations

    -> Example:

        import java.util.Map;
        import java.util.function.Function;
        import java.util.stream.Collectors;
        import java.util.stream.Stream;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> Problem:
        -> Too many import statements.
        -> Boilerplate code increased.
        -> Large programs often contained many imports.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Alternative Earlier Approach

    -> We could reduce imports using:
    
        import java.util.*;
        import java.util.function.*;
        import java.util.stream.*;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> But still:
        -> Multiple package imports were required.
        -> Developers still needed to know exact package names.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Java Enhancement

    -> Java introduced Module Import Declarations through:
    
        -> JEP 511

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Main Idea

    -> Instead of importing individual packages,
       Java now allows importing an entire module.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Syntax

        import module moduleName;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example

        import module java.base;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> What Happens Internally?

    -> Java imports:
    
        -> All public top-level classes/interfaces
        -> From packages exported by that module.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example

    -> java.base module exports packages like:
    
        -> java.util
        -> java.util.function
        -> java.util.stream
        -> java.lang
        -> java.io
        -> etc.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> Therefore:

        import module java.base;

       automatically makes classes available from all these exported packages.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example Conversion

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> Earlier Code:

        import java.util.Map;
        import java.util.function.Function;
        import java.util.stream.Collectors;
        import java.util.stream.Stream;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> Now Simplified As:

        import module java.base;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Important Benefit

    -> Reduces:
    
        -> Boilerplate imports
        -> Package-level import management
        -> Repeated import statements

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Important Concept

    -> Module import declaration performs:
    
        -> On-demand imports

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> Meaning:
        -> Classes are imported when required.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Syntax Structure

        import module M;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> Here:
    
        -> M = Module name

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> What Gets Imported?

    -> Module import declaration imports:

        -> All public top-level classes/interfaces
        -> From packages exported by module M

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Additional Important Feature

    -> It also imports:
    
        -> Packages exported by modules
        -> that are READ by module M

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Why This Is Useful?

    -> Many modules internally depend on other modules.
    -> Module import declarations automatically make related APIs available.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example

        import module java.sql;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> java.sql internally depends on:
    
        -> java.logging
        -> java.xml

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> Therefore:
        -> Their exported packages also become available automatically.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Ambiguous Imports Problem

    -> Sometimes multiple modules/packages may contain:
    
        -> Classes with same simple name.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example

    -> java.awt.List
    -> java.util.List

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> If both imported:
    
        -> Compiler becomes confused.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example

        import module java.desktop;
        import module java.base;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> Compiler Error:

        reference to List is ambiguous

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Why?

    -> Because:
    
        -> java.awt.List
        -> java.util.List

       both are visible.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Another Example

    -> java.awt.Label
    -> java.lang.classfile.Label

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> Compiler cannot decide:
    
        -> Which Label class to use.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Solution for Ambiguous Imports

    -> Use single-type-import declarations.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example

        import module java.desktop;
        import module java.base;

        import java.awt.Label;
        import java.awt.List;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Why This Works?

    -> Single-type-import declarations take higher priority.
    -> They shadow conflicting imported types.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Shadowing Concept

    -> Shadowing means:
    
        -> One declaration hides another declaration
           with same name.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example

        import java.awt.List;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> This shadows:
    
        java.util.List

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Important Rule

    -> Single-type-import declarations have higher priority than:
    
        -> module imports
        -> on-demand imports

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Another Simplification

    -> Instead of:

        import java.awt.Label;
        import java.awt.List;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> We can use:

        import java.awt.*;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Why This Works?

    -> Type-import-on-demand declarations can also shadow module imports.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Compact Source Files and Module Imports

    -> Every compact source file automatically behaves like:

        import module java.base;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Meaning

    -> Compact source files automatically gain access to:
    
        -> All exported packages from java.base module.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Therefore in compact source files:

    -> Many imports become unnecessary.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example

        void main() {

            Map<String, String> map = new HashMap<>();

            Stream.of("A", "B")
                  .forEach(System.out::println);
        }

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> Here:
    
        -> Map
        -> HashMap
        -> Stream

       work without explicit imports in compact source files.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Why?

    -> Because:
    
        import module java.base;

       is automatically applied internally.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Importing Entire Standard Java API

    -> Java also allows importing:
    
        import module java.se;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> What is java.se?

    -> java.se is a larger module containing:
    
        -> Entire standard Java API.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example

        import module java.se;

        import java.awt.*;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Benefit

    -> Almost all standard Java APIs become available.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Important Note

    -> java.se is NOT automatically included for unnamed module.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Therefore compilation may require:

        --add-modules java.se

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Example Compilation

        javac --add-modules java.se FruitApp.java

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Important Change in JDK 24+

    -> Earlier:
    
        -> java.se did NOT transitively depend on java.base

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    -> From newer Java versions:
    
        -> java.se can now transitively expose java.base
           for module import declarations.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Important Terms

    | Term | Meaning |
    |------|----------|
    | Module Import Declaration | Imports all exported packages from module |
    | On-Demand Import | Imports types when needed |
    | Shadowing | One declaration hides another |
    | Ambiguous Import | Multiple matching class names cause conflict |
    | Transitive Dependence | One module indirectly exposes another module |

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Benefits of Module Import Declarations

    -> Reduces import boilerplate
    -> Easier beginner experience
    -> Cleaner code
    -> Better readability
    -> Easier access to standard APIs
    -> Works well with compact source files

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Limitations / Cautions

    -> May introduce ambiguous imports.
    -> Large modules may expose many classes.
    -> Developers must still understand package conflicts.
    -> Enterprise projects may still prefer explicit imports for readability.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

=> Simple Mental Model

    -> Earlier Java:
    
        "Import packages individually."

    -> Modern Java:
    
        "Import an entire module at once."